NS-PIE — Documentation Master Plan (Aligned to NS-GGP Canonical Template)

Purpose

This document defines the authoritative documentation master plan for PIE (Product InsightIQ Engine), strictly aligned to the NS-GGP canonical document structure (000–014).

PIE is Northfield Solidarity’s product research and product intelligence engine. It is responsible for:

market and product discovery

product catalog intelligence (attributes, pricing, demand proxies)

competitor and listing analysis

sourcing/logistics signal capture (vendor/3PL/lead-times)

roadmap outputs for building or selling products

packaging insight into actionable work (CWP tasks) and simulations (SIM)

PIE is not:

a governance authority (GGP)

the integration gateway itself (MUX)

the financial ledger (FLO)

the operational work coordinator (CWP)

PIE produces insights, structured datasets, and recommended actions, all governed by GGP.

PIE Documentation Index (Canonical)

NS-PIE-000 — CHARTER

Purpose: Define why PIE exists.

Scope

Mission and non-goals

What “Product InsightIQ” means in NS

Boundaries vs DRE/SIG/SIM/MUX/FLO/CWP

Core outputs (insight packages, product candidates, research dossiers)

Outputs

One-paragraph mission

Core responsibilities (allowed actions)

Explicit non-responsibilities

NS-PIE-001 — OVERVIEW

Purpose: Provide executive overview of PIE capabilities and operating model.

Scope

Primary use cases:

top-selling product discovery

niche validation

competitor listing and pricing analysis

supplier/3PL shortlist generation

build-vs-buy recommendation

Data sources (internal and external categories)

Insight pipeline stages (collect → normalize → score → recommend)

Reliability and quality posture

Outputs

Capability map

Typical user journeys (operator and automation)

NS-PIE-002 — TAXONOMY

Purpose: Define the canonical vocabulary for product intelligence.

Scope

Entities: ProductCandidate, Listing, Offer, Vendor, Supplier, 3PL, Market, Channel

Signals: price, rank, reviews, sentiment, inventory, lead time, shipping cost

Metrics: margin estimate, demand proxy, volatility, risk tier

Research artifacts: Dossier, EvidenceRefs, SourceAttribution

Scoring and ranking terms (confidence, freshness, coverage)

Outputs

Terms and definitions

Naming conventions (product_id, candidate_id, dossier_id)

NS-PIE-003 — ARCHITECTURE

Purpose: Describe PIE’s system architecture and engine boundaries.

Scope

Data ingestion pathways (via MUX + DRE/SIG)

Normalization/feature extraction

Scoring + ranking layer

Knowledge store(s) and index/search

Output packaging to CWP and SIM

Observability via LUM

Governance gates via GGP

Outputs

Component diagram

Dataflow diagrams (sources → insight outputs)

NS-PIE-004 — LIFECYCLE

Purpose: Define the lifecycle of research, candidates, and insight outputs.

Scope

Candidate lifecycle (discovered → enriched → scored → shortlisted → approved → executed/archived)

Dossier lifecycle (draft → reviewed → published → deprecated)

Refresh and recrawl schedules

Human review checkpoints

Outputs

Lifecycle state machines

Refresh/retention guidelines

NS-PIE-005 — DECISION

Purpose: Define decision points and governance gates.

Scope

When GGP approval is required:

using a new data source

scraping/terms-of-service risk decisions

vendor outreach automation

committing spend (samples, subscriptions)

publishing recommendations to downstream execution

Evidence requirements for “recommended product” decisions

Risk tiers and confidence thresholds

Outputs

Decision matrix

Required evidence per decision class

